  "prompt": "Which sorting algorithms are used practically?",
  "response": "Several sorting algorithms are used in practice, depending on the specific requirements and characteristics of the data:\n\n1. Quicksort\n- Average time complexity: O(n log n)\n- Widely used in standard libraries\n- Good performance for large datasets\n- In-place sorting\n- Efficient for random access data structures\n\n2. Merge Sort\n- Stable sort\n- Consistent O(n log n) time complexity\n- Good for linked lists\n- External sorting\n- Used in file sorting and database operations\n\n3. Heapsort\n- In-place sorting\n- Guaranteed O(n log n) time complexity\n- Used in priority queues\n- Good for embedded systems\n\n4. Timsort\n- Hybrid sorting algorithm\n- Default sorting in Python and Java\n- Combines merge sort and insertion sort\n- Efficient for real-world data\n- Adaptive sorting\n\n5. Introsort\n- Hybrid of quicksort, heapsort, and insertion sort\n- Default in C++ STL\n- Guarantees O(n log n) worst-case performance\n\n6. Insertion Sort\n- Efficient for small datasets\n- Stable sort\n- Used in hybrid algorithms\n- Good for nearly sorted data\n\n7. Radix Sort\n- Linear time complexity O(nk)\n- Used for integer sorting\n- Efficient for fixed-length keys\n\nEach algorithm has strengths for different scenarios and data characteristics.",
